with chronological age and included modules enriched for 'Translational 
elongation', 'Cytolysis' and 'DNA metabolic process'. In an independent study of 
3535 individuals, four of five modules consistently associated with 
chronological age, underpinning the robustness of the approach. We found three 
of five modules to be significantly enriched with aging-related genes, as 
defined by the GenAge database, and association with prospective survival at 
high ages for one of the modules including ASF1A. The hereby-detected 
age-associated and consistently coexpressed PPI modules therefore may provide a 
molecular basis for future research into mechanisms underlying human aging.

